<p>
Similarly, interviews are used to assess applicants’ academic excellence and potential but, in addition, they provide a way for universities to assess applicants’ passion for subjects they wish to study. Oxford and Cambridge are famous for how important interviews are in their admissions process.  
Oxbridge applicants are usually interviewed by 2 or 3 tutors, and may have up to two interviews with each interview being 20-30 minutes long. Students will often be asked to talk about what interests them about the subject they are applying to study, based on their personal statement, or books or articles they have read recently.</p>

<p>
 Conditional offers are given by end of March where applicants must meet certain A-Level/ IB/ Pre-U examination grades as demanded by universities in order to secure their university entrance. </p>

<p>
Young Tutors believes that undergraduate and graduate students at these universities 
can be excellent tutors because they have been through the relevant national curriculum 
examinations and obtained top grades. Additionally, they may be able to offer valuable 
advice on applications to these universities.


<h2>US universities</h2>

<p>
 Although all elite universities look for students with excellent <b>academic records</b>, Ivy League Universities for example, Harvard, Yale and Princeton) and the best Liberal Arts Colleges (for example, Williams College, Amherst College and Pomona College) in the USA also put a strong emphasis on <b>extra-curricular achievements</b>, personal/ leadership qualities and the student’s commitment to attending a particular institution when deciding which  applicants to offer places to.
</p>
