<p class="middle-box-p with-title">
<b>College Essays</b></p>
<p class="middle-box-p with-title">
Each essay is 500-750 words long, and each university sets its own essay questions for admission. 
However, the essay topics are similar for most universities: typically, they will ask you to discuss 
your academic background and motivation, give your perspective on a topical issue and/ or analyse some of your personal experiences and set out your goals and ambitions.</p>

<p class="middle-box-p with-title">
<b>Standardised Tests</b>
<br/>
<p class="middle-box-p with-title">
    Applicants need to take either the <a href="http://sat.collegeboard.org/" target="_blank"><span class="sub_txt2_style10">SAT</span></a> or the 
            <a href="http://www.act.org/products/k-12-act-test/" target="_blank"><span class="sub_txt2_style10">ACT</span></a> which are offered several times a year throughout numerous sites in the UK.
<br/><br/>    SAT – tests in Critical Reading, Mathematics and Writing

<br/><br/>    ACT – tests in English, Mathematics, Reading and Science Reasoning

<br/><br/>    Some of the most competitive institutions will also ask you to take the <a href="http://www.act.org/aap/writing/" target="_blank"><span class="sub_txt2_style10">ACT writing test</span></a> and/ or <a href="http://sat.collegeboard.org/about-tests/sat-subject-tests" target="_blank"><span class="sub_txt2_style10">SAT Subject Tests</span></a>

<br/><br/>    SAT Subject Tests – 20 multiple choice questions on individual subjects

<br/><br/>    ACT writing test – 30 minute essay test</p>

<p class="middle-box-p with-title">
<b>Peer Recommendation</b>
<br/>
US interviews are conducted by alumni and are not so much as intense as Oxbridge ones but more to check whether the applicant is sure about the university or not.
</p>

